g.text: Parasite lifetime reproductive success is determined by both genetic variation and phenotypically
plastic life history traits that respond to host quality and external environment. In this study we use the
to test aspects of life history theory. We evaluate species
life history strategies when grown on a common host, document phenotypic plasticity when grown on
many different hosts, and relate our observations to trait differences recorded in the wild. We find
in a common garden and in the field exhibit a range of life history strategies that differ
between species that transition rapidly to flower at the expense of early season growth, and those that
invest in vegetative growth and delay flowering. However, aspects of life history show extensive
phenotypic plasticity in response to host quality, and demonstrate the costs of attaching to a low-
quality host. Our experiments suggest life history strategies in a generalist parasitic plant are the
product of natural selection on traits related to growth and flowering, while host quality may be a
primary determinant of lifetime reproductive success.
Keywords: flowering time; host range; life history evolution; parasitic plants; phenotypic plasticity
